<ue5><m0>Diverse group meets<ql>
on Quebec strategy<ql>
<m1><ue5><ep>
<m0> <m0>OTTAWA <m0>(--) Six months after sovereigntists nearly won a referendum in Quebec, old war horses charged out of the past and into the breach Saturday with ideas for keeping the country together.<ep>
   About 100 prominent Canadians (--) among them former Prime Minister Joe Clark, former Alberta Premier Peter Lougheed and onetime Quebec Liberal leader Claude Ryan (--) met in Ottawa to formulate a plan for keeping Quebec in Canada.<ep>
   Many of the recommendations echo ideas from the Clark and Ryan eras, while others mirror the Chretien government's February throne speech.<ep>
   What may be new is that consenus was reached among a fairly disparate group of Canadians that included business leaders, academics and former leaders.<ep>
   Conference 2000, sponsored by the Business Council on National Issues, will deliver its report to the prime minister and each of the premiers. Changes the group says are needed in the next six months include freer trade among the provinces and a federal withdrawal from labor market adjustment and training.<ql>
