<ue5><m0>Designers fight<ql>
over Olympic garb<ql>
<m1><ue5><ep>
<m0> <m0>TORONTO <m0>(--) Two Toronto clothing designers are locked in a legal struggle over what Canada's athletes will wear at the Summer Games in Atlanta.<ep>
   The dispute threatens to keep the specially designed opening-ceremony outfits on the rack when the games open July 19.<ep>
   For his creations to mark the 100th anniversary of the modern Olympics, designer James Yunker was inspired by the turn of the century: antique-white blazers and slacks for the men, and antique-red vests and long dresses for the women.<ep>
   But another Toronto designer, Hasmig Possian, says Yunker copied her work and is seeking a court injunction, Yunker's lawyer says.<ep>
   Possian's bid for an injunction goes before a Federal Court judge today in Toronto. If she's successful, it's unlikely the Olympic association could commission replacement outfits in time for the opening.<ql>
