<styl>rdup,11p1<ql>
<ue5><m0>Study: Bad air<ql>
killing Canadians<ql>
<m1><ue5><ep>
<m0> <m0>OTTAWA <m0>(--) Bad air is killing Canadians, a new Health Canada study says.<ep>
   The study of Toronto-area hospital records found that when the air is polluted, an extra two to three people a day die from heart and respiratory diseases. Most are 65 or older.<ep>
   That's an increase of 2 to 4 percent for these diseases, the department says.<ep>
   The study area covered metropolitan Toronto, home to about 2.5 million people, over a 20-year period ending in 1990.<ep>
   A Health Canada investigator says Montreal, though it has a slightly different mix of pollutants, has a similar overall air quality to Toronto and may show similar extra deaths. Ottawa, with cleaner air, probably does not.<ql>
