<styl>rdup,11p1<ql>
<ue5><m0>Specialty channels<ql>
seek spot on dial<ql>
<m1><ue5><ep>
<m0>  <m0>OTTAWA <m0>(--) Rug rats and retirees, sports fans and sci-fi buffs are among TV viewers who could have more channels to surf a year from now.<ep>
   The federal broadcast regulator begins hearing a new round of specialty channel applications today, with 40 applicants lined up for precious space in the TV lineup.<ep>
   The offerings include all-day headline news channels, comedy, kids' shows, sports, history, seniors' programs, outdoor life, ethnic and other programs.<ep>
   It's anyone's guess how many will be licensed by the Canadian Radio-Television and Telecommunications Commission. After the last round of applications in 1994, eight channels were awarded, including two French.<ep>
   Licenses will probably be granted next fall, with winners starting up in 1997.<ql>
