<ue5><m0>People afraid despite<ql>
alleged killer's arrest<ql>
<m1><ue5><ep>
<m0> <m0>ABBOTSFORD, B.C. <m0>(--) After seven months of fear and frustration as police hunted for the jeering killer of 16-year-old Tanya Smith, nervous doubts still trouble residents of this city, who never dreamed such terrifying events could happen in their midst.<ep>
   Terry Driver, the man arrested and charged in the case on Friday, is slated for a brief court appearance today.<ep>
   Yet huge questions and incongruities remain. No one in this city of 105,000, known for its placid farmland and active church groups, seems ready to let their guard down.<ep>
   Driver, a 31-year-old print shop worker, was charged Friday with first-degree murder in Smith's death, and attempted murder in the beating of her friend Misty Cockerill, 16. Cockerill remains in hiding despite the arrest.<ql>
