<styl>rdup,11p1<ql>
<ue5><m0>Appeal filed to stop<ql>
girl's deportation<ql>
<m1><ue5><ep>
<m0> <m0>TORONTO <m0>(--) An appeal has been filed in Federal Court to stop the deportation of a 3-year-old Somali girl whose refugee claim was rejected.<ep>
   An Immigration and Refugee Board ruled last week that Iftin, whose last name can't be revealed because she is a claimant, is not a refugee and should be removed from Canada.<ep>
   ``This is inhumane,'' said her lawyer, Geraldine Sadoway. ``In war, it's the little kids who are the most endangered.''<ep>
   Sadoway said the child was sent here with an adult by her parents in May 1994. Her parents and five siblings live in a refugee camp in Kenya.<ep>
   ``She was young and sick and they didn't think she would survive,'' Sadoway said.<ep>
   But the board threw out the little girl's refugee claim because her father is a citizen of Ethiopia who moved to Somalia but never obtained citizenship there.<ql>
